SEOUL, Jan. 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's economy grew 4 percent last year, marking the highest growth in 11 years, central bank data showed Tuesday. Real gross domestic product (GDP), adjusted for inflation, expanded 4 percent in 2021 from a year earlier, according to the Bank of Korea (BOK). It was the fastest increase in 11 years since 2010, rebounding from the 0.9 percent reduction in 2020. In the fourth quarter of 2021, the real GDP gained 1.1 percent compared to three months earlier, after climbing 1.7 percent in the first quarter, 0.8 percent in the second quarter, and 0.3 percent in the third quarter of last year. The real GDP declined 1.3 percent and 3.2 percent in the first and second quarters of 2020, before rising 2.2 percent and 1.1 percent in the third and fourth quarters of the year.  â– 